            <h2>10.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Supplement Your Diet</h2>
            <p><br /></p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/skinsup.jpg" />
            <p><br /></p>
            <p>If your looking to supplement your diet to help improve the health and vibrancy of your skin then <b>choosing vitamins, minerals, and various superfoods that target collagen production is the way to go</b>.</p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <p><b>There are a number of foods and supplements you can use to stimulate collagen production:</b></p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <div style="background-color:rgba(200,200,200,0.1);padding:8px;">
                <h2 style="text-align:center;background-color:transparent;"><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3673383/" target="_blank">Vitamin C</a></h2>
                <p></p>

                <p>
                    <b>Vitamin C is a very rapidly depleted resource in the body</b>, and unlike some other vitamins,
                    the body cannot manufacture or synthesise it on its own. <b>It has to be included in your diet.</b>
                </p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p>You can find moisturisers and creams with added vitamin C to be applied directly to the skin, but <b>you can also get vitamin C from many foods.</b></p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <ul style="text-align:center;padding:0;">
                    <li><b>Most fruits contain vitamin C</b></li>
                    <li><b>Leafy green salads and vegetables, such as kale or broccoli.</b></li>
                    <li><b>Any root vegetables</b></li>
                    <li><b>Red and green peppers.</b></li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <p><br /></p>
            <div style="background-color:rgba(200,200,200,0.1);padding:8px;">
                <h2 style="text-align:center;background-color:transparent;"><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3583886/" target="_blank">Hyaluronic Acid</a></h2>
                <p></p>

                <p><b>Hyaluronic acid is a core ingredient required for the production of collagen</b>. Most whole-grain plant-based foods will contain a sufficient level of hyaluronic acid.</p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p>If you increase your consumption of garlic, onions, ginger, carrots, beans, nuts and seeds – <b>you should have no problem reaping the benefits of enhanced collagen production</b>.</p>
            </div><p><br /></p>
            <div style="background-color:rgba(200,200,200,0.1);padding:8px;">
                <h2 style="text-align:center;background-color:transparent;"><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2883372/" target="_blank">Aloe Vera</a></h2>
                <p></p>
                <p>Studies have found that <b>Aloe Vera ingested orally on a daily basis actually reduced facial wrinkles and improved elasticity</b> in photo-aged skin.</p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p>
                    <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2883372/" target="_blank">This dermatological study</a> proved with significance that a
                    regular intake of <b>aloe vera supplementation increased collagen production</b>, while additionally
                    decreasing the expression of a gene associated with reducing collagen production.
                </p>
            </div><p><br /></p>
            <div style="background-color:rgba(200,200,200,0.1);padding:8px;">
                <h2 style="text-align:center;background-color:transparent;"><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3249911/" target="_blank">Antioxidants</a></h2>
                <p></p>
                <p><b>Antioxidants, in my opinion, are the most important supplementary substances involved in maintaining good health</b> – with a general healthy diet.</p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p>
                    <b>They are the agents in your body that collect and remove free radicals.</b> Free-radicals contribute to many health problems, diseases, cataracts, and cancers. They are unstable and highly reactive molecules that wreak havoc on a cellular
                    level, damaging cell membranes, DNA, proteins, and carbohydrates.
                </p>
                <p><br /></p>
                <p><b style="background-color:yellow;">Not only, do antioxidants remove toxins and cleanse the body, they also prevent the formation of radicals.</b></p>
            </div><p><br /></p>
            <div style="padding:10px;border:2px dotted orange;background-color:rgba(255,200,50,0.05);text-align:center;">
