                            <img style="width:50%;" src="~/Content/Images/brushingteeth.jpg" />
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px solid rgba(40,50,60,0.05); background-color:rgba(100,100,100,0.05); padding:10px;">
                                <p>
                                    This ensures the bristles of the toothbrush are <b>specifically targeting those areas that are most prone to the build-up of residual sugary deposits </b>from your food and beverages, and also the breeding ground for bacterial plaque residues.
                                </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>
                                    The areas of the teeth that <b>need to be cleaned</b> are predominately those that are <b>not</b> <i>naturally worn away in the process of eating foods.</i> Let the toothbrush clean these crevices and this will prevent the cumulative formation of bacterial
                                    plaque.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><strong>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;Try to use a circular motion.</strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px solid rgba(40,50,60,0.05); background-color:rgba(100,100,100,0.05); padding:10px;">
                                <p><b>Dental plaque can also form in between the teeth.</b> Moving the toothbrush in a <i>circular motion</i> can let the bristles slide along the <i>inner folds between the teeth</i> and remove any residues that may have been neglected otherwise.</p>
                            </div><p><br /></p>
                            <p><strong>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;Brush the outside surfaces AND the inside surfaces.</strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px solid rgba(40,50,60,0.05); background-color:rgba(100,100,100,0.05); padding:10px;">
                                <p><b>Many people brush their teeth routinely purely for aesthetical purposes.</b> This means that <span style="background-color:yellow;"><b>many people have a build-up of plaque developing on the back of their teeth</b></span> – <b>the parts they cannot see in the mirror.</b></p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p><b>It is important not to neglect the back of all your teeth</b> since this is an area that is even more prone to the build-up of, not only plaque but also dental calculus.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <blockquote>Focus on brushing into the area <b>where the back of the tooth meets the gum</b> for the best results.</blockquote>
                            </div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><strong>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;Don’t forget your molars!</strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px solid rgba(40,50,60,0.05); background-color:rgba(100,100,100,0.05); padding:10px;">
                                <p>For the molar teeth at the back, they have a very wide top surface. This can be considered a third side.<b> Clean this part with a light forward and backward motion</b> with the toothbrush aiming directly down on the teeth.</p>
                            </div><p><br /></p>
                            <p><strong>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;Brush lightly and carefully.</strong></p>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <div style="border:1px solid rgba(40,50,60,0.05); background-color:rgba(100,100,100,0.05); padding:10px;">
                                <p>
                                    Brushing your teeth is a self-care exercise, <i>not an industrial sanding job</i>. You will not be able to brush away all your plaque with <i>horrendously rapid or furious toothbrush scraping</i>.<b>
                                        This is so bad for the enamel, not to mention your
                                        gums!
                                    </b>
                                </p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <p>Instead, brush <b>lightly</b>, and <i>spend time going around all your teeth</i> with the steps mentioned above.</p>
                                <p><br /></p>
                                <blockquote>A consistently light and regular approach to brushing teeth is enough to prevent the build-up of plaque and calculus.</blockquote>
                            </div>
                            <p><br /></p>
                            <p><strong>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;Take as long as is necessary</strong></p>
