            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p><span style="color: black; background-color: white;">A healthy, plant-based diet aims to maximize the consumption of nutrient-dense plant foods while minimizing processed foods and animal foods, and products. It requires a higher consumption of vegetables, fruits, beans, peas, nuts, and seeds.</span></p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p><strong style="color: black; background-color: white;">What are the benefits of a whole-grain plant-based diet?</strong></p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p><span style="color: black; background-color: white;">A meta-analysis study (a study of 87 scientific studies) found that a whole-grain plant-based diet is effective for weight loss, and reducing the risk of heart disease and high blood pressure. </span></p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p><span style="color: black; background-color: white;">They also found that vegetarians' diets contained more nutrients and vegetarians were less nutrient deficient as a result. There was a correlation with a reduced rate of diabetes and heart disease. </span></p>

            <p id="third" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;">
            </p>
            <H1><strong>WHY SHOULD I REDUCE MY CONSUMPTION OF ANIMAL PRODUCTS?</strong></H1>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p><span style="color: black; background-color: white;">Eating food that does not strictly meet the ‘plant-based’ criteria, such as meat or fish, is not illegal or restricted in a whole-grain plant-based diet, but it should be minimized as much as possible. </span></p>

            <p id="thirda" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;">
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Are animal products unhealthy?</strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>Meat is now a major health concern and the statistics are quite troubling. The consumption of meat has been attributed to heart disease, strokes, diabetes, cancer, and many other diseases. Nobody needs to eat meat, and it's not good for you. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <H5><strong>WHAT ABOUT THE GOVERNMENT GUIDELINES?</strong></H5>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>People who follow the UK government guidelines which suggest you eat around 76 grams of red and processed meat a day are still 20% more likely to develop bowel cancer than those who eat only 20 grams per day; according to a study jointly funded by Cancer Research UK and published in the International Journal of Epidemiology [3]. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <H5><strong>WHAT DOES THE WORLD HEALTH ORGANISATION THINK?</strong></H5>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>The World Cancer Research Fund (WCRF) says that people should “Eat mostly foods of plant origin, limit intake of red meat, and avoid processed meat.” According to the World Health Organisation, just one hot dog or a few strips of bacon consumed daily increases cancer risk by 18% [2].</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <H5><strong>OXFORD UNIVERSITY LINKED CHICKEN CONSUMPTION TO BLOOD CANCER</strong></H5>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>Oxford University found that the consumption of chicken is associated with a higher risk of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, a type of blood cancer. It was also attributed to higher rates of prostate cancer in men. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>Even handling raw poultry while preparing and cooking food due to various blood cancers that can be attributed to viruses of poultry. Studies have found that people who work in continual exposure to raw poultry have higher-than-normal odds of developing cancer.</p>

            <p id="thirdb" style="margin-top:-50px;margin-bottom:100px;">
            </p>
            <p><strong>Is it ethical to consume animal products?</strong></p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>There are 7.8 billion human beings on the planet. Every person will consume on average 821,000 calories every year. This energy must come from somewhere. Sunlight energy is collected by organisms and transferred around the food chain. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <H5><strong>DO HUMANS CONSUME TOO MANY ANIMAL PRODUCTS?</strong></H5><p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>The highest calorie foods are higher up the food chain. These foods have more calories per gram of fibre. Throughout the world, animal products provide about 36 percent of the calorie content of the food supply.</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>That’s about 295,000 calories per person, per year. An average carnivorous person will eat nearly 7000 animals in their lifetime. According to the Vegetarian Calculator, this equates to roughly 11 cows, 27 pigs, 2,400 chickens, 80 turkeys, 30 sheep, and 4,500 fish [1]. </p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <H5><strong>IS THE CONSUMPTION OF ANIMAL PRODUCTS DECREASING?</strong></H5><p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>
                <img style="width:100%;" src="~/Content/Images/fghfdg.jpg" />
            </p>
            <p><br /></p>
            <blockquote style="text-align:center;">NO!</blockquote>
            <p>
            </p>
            <p>As seen in the graph above, the increase in global wealth, paired with the global population explosion, has led to a <b>dramatic incline in demand for animal-based food products</b>.</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p>There are more than <b>150 billion animals slaughtered every year</b>. In America, they slaughter about <b>25 million farm animals every day</b>, and every year, 850 million never make it to the slaughterhouse because they die prematurely from stress-induced disease or injury. Check out the <a href="https://thevegancalculator.com/">Vegan Calculator</a> to see the live numbers.</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
            <p><a href="https://www.joeycarbstrong.com/">Joey Carbstrong</a> is a vegan activist who debates the issue all over the world. Here is a good example of one of Joey’s street debates.</p>
            <p>
                <br>
            </p>
